abstract: TOPEKA, Kan., Nov. 3. -- Political affairs in Kansas are in a chaotic state, such as was never before seen. The Farmers' Alliance, organized first solely for self-protection and self-instruction, was, one year ago, not unlike the dozen other organizations in the State, small in numbers and without particular influence. It grew, however, like the fabulous pumpkin vine in Southern California, and threatened in a short time to entwine and choke all opposing parties.

abstract: BOSTON, Nov. 3. -- The Liliputians, who achieved such success at Niblo's and the Metropolitan Opera House in New-York, appeared in their spectacular play, "The Pupil in Magic," at the Hollis Street Theatre in this city for the first time to-night. The large house was packed to the doors. The audience, composed almost entirely of Americans, with hardly a German among them, was most enthusiastic and applauded the Liliputians again and again.

abstract: OTTAWA, Ontario, Nov. 3. -- The Governor General has received a petition from England praying that the sentence of death, recently passed upon Reginald Birchall, now in jail at Woodstock, Ontario, be commuted to imprisonment for life. Unless the Governor General intervenes, the prisoner will be hanged on Nov. 14. The English petition is signed by 2,000 persons, including Birchall's mother, Oswald Birchall, half-brother of the prisoner, and rector of Buscot, besides prominent clergymen.

abstract: The National Cross-Country Association succeeded in deciding its junior championship race at Morris Park yesterday. abstract: NEW-HAVEN, Nov. 15. -- At the beginning of the season the Yale outlook in football was not at all encouraging. Rhodes, Heffelfinger, Hartwell, and McClung were the only players of last year's team that could be counted on to play this Fall. abstract: PINE RIDGE AGENCY, South Dakota, via Rushville, Neb., Nov. 29. -- Troopers of the Ninth Cavalry were under orders to march at a moment's notice last night. It had been reported that the Rosebud Indians and some of Little Wound's band were circling in a war dance and were prepared to fight. The defiant attitude of the Indians started a furious telegraphic correspondence between the military officers here and the authorities at Washington.

abstract: The bargain buying by the public, and the broken lot purchasing, have stopped. The market is therefore again narrowing down to the professionals, and to their operations the activity of the past week must be mainly attributed.
